msgid "Congratulations! You've completed the hardest part of the Algebraic Limit Theorem.\n"
"\n"
"Postscript:\n"
"**Why would you think to add and subtract ┬¦0?**\n"
"\n"
"Think about the product rule in calculus: ┬¦1. Multiplication always corresponds to a rectangle. When you have two quantities ┬¦2 and ┬¦3 both changing, the change in their product ┬¦4 can be visualized as the change in area:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦5\n"
"\n"
"The total change is ┬¦6.\n"
"\n"
"In our proof, we replaced ┬¦7 with ┬¦8 (adding and subtracting ┬¦9) to get the same decomposition. The ┬¦10 term (the tiny corner) gets absorbed into ┬¦11, and since both factors are small, it doesn't cause problems.\n"
"\n"
"This geometric picture explains the algebraic trick: we're decomposing the area difference into two manageable strips that we can control independently.\n"
"\n"
"# Algebraic Limit Theorem - Complete!\n"
"\n"
"You can now:\n"
"- **Add** sequences: if ┬¦12 and ┬¦13, then ┬¦14\n"
"- **Multiply by constants**: if ┬¦15, then ┬¦16\n"
"- **Multiply** sequences: if ┬¦17 and ┬¦18, then ┬¦19\n"
"- **Invert** (when limit is nonzero): if ┬¦20, then ┬¦21\n"
"\n"
"This is incredibly powerful! For any algebraic combination of convergent sequences, you can compute the limit by just plugging in the individual limits.\n"
"\n"
"**Example:** If ┬¦22 and ┬¦23, what is\n"
"┬¦24\n"
"\n"
"**Answer:** ┬¦25 (provided the denominator ŌēĀ 0).\n"
"\n"
"You can build this up step by step using the algebraic limit rules!\n"
"\n"
"**Note:** The case where ┬¦26 or ┬¦27 is left as an exercise. The proof requires slightly different techniques since you can't divide by ┬¦28 or ensure ┬¦29 is bounded away from zero. Try it yourself!"
