#: Game.Levels.L22Levels.L02
msgid "# Level 2: Uniform Convergence\n"
"\n"
"Welcome to one of the most profound and beautiful theorems in real analysis! After seeing how nicely continuous functions compose, you might think that continuous functions always \"play well\" together. But as we hinted in our introduction dialogue, this isn't always the case when infinite processes are involved.\n"
"\n"
"## The Crisis We're Solving\n"
"\n"
"Remember Cauchy's mistake? In the early 1800s, even the great Augustin-Louis Cauchy \"proved\" that the pointwise limit of continuous functions must be continuous. His proof looked rock-solidŌĆöuntil counterexamples like ┬¦0 on ┬¦1 shattered the illusion.\n"
"\n"
"The problem isn't with Cauchy's logicŌĆöit's with pointwise convergence itself. When we say ┬¦2 pointwise, we're saying:\n"
"\n"
"**Pointwise**: \"For each point ┬¦3, eventually the functions ┬¦4 get close to ┬¦5\"\n"
"\n"
"But \"eventually\" might mean very different things at different points! At some points, ┬¦6 might converge to ┬¦7 after just 10 steps. At nearby points, it might take 1000 steps. This non-uniformity destroys continuity.\n"
"\n"
"## The Beautiful Solution: Uniform Convergence\n"
"\n"
"**Uniform convergence** fixes this by demanding the same rate of convergence everywhere:\n"
"\n"
"**Uniform**: \"There's a single moment in time after which all the functions ┬¦8 are close to ┬¦9 at all points simultaneously\"\n"
"\n"
"## The New Definition: ┬¦10\n"
"\n"
"┬¦11\n"
"\n"
"**Read this carefully**: For every tolerance ┬¦12, there exists a \"convergence moment\" ┬¦13 such that for all later functions ┬¦14 (with ┬¦15) and for all points ┬¦16 simultaneously, we have ┬¦17.\n"
"\n"
"## The Quantifier Order Revolution\n"
"\n"
"The difference between pointwise and uniform convergence is entirely about **quantifier order**:\n"
"\n"
"- **Pointwise**: ┬¦18\n"
"- **Uniform**: ┬¦19\n"
"\n"
"In pointwise convergence, ┬¦20 can depend on both ┬¦21 and ┬¦22. In uniform convergence, ┬¦23 depends only on ┬¦24ŌĆöthe same ┬¦25 must work for *every* point ┬¦26.\n"
"\n"
"## Why This Saves Continuity\n"
"\n"
"Think back to our failed attempt to prove continuity with pointwise convergence. The breakdown was:\n"
"\n"
"1. We picked ┬¦27 to approximate ┬¦28 well at our point ┬¦29\n"
"2. We used ┬¦30's continuity to control behavior near ┬¦31\n"
"3. **DISASTER**: We needed ┬¦32 to approximate ┬¦33 well at nearby points ┬¦34, but our choice of ┬¦35 was only guaranteed to work at ┬¦36!\n"
"\n"
"With uniform convergence:\n"
"1. We pick ┬¦37 to approximate ┬¦38 well **everywhere simultaneously**\n"
"2. We use ┬¦39's continuity to control behavior near ┬¦40\n"
"3. **SUCCESS**: Since ┬¦41 approximates ┬¦42 uniformly, it automatically works at all nearby points ┬¦43!\n"
"\n"
"## The Theorem You'll Prove\n"
"\n"
"**Theorem**: If each ┬¦44 is continuous and ┬¦45 converges uniformly to ┬¦46, then ┬¦47 is continuous.\n"
"\n"
"This is the theorem that rehabilitated Cauchy's intuition. Continuous functions do preserve continuity under limitsŌĆöyou just need the right kind of limit!\n"
"\n"
"## Your Proof Strategy: The ┬¦48 Trick\n"
"\n"
"To show ┬¦49 is continuous at a point ┬¦50, given ┬¦51, you'll want to show ┬¦52 when ┬¦53 is close to ┬¦54.\n"
"\n"
"Use the triangle inequality:\n"
"┬¦55\n"
"\n"
"Make each term less than ┬¦56:\n"
"- **First term**: Uniform convergence gives you this everywhere\n"
"- **Second term**: Continuity of ┬¦57 gives you this near ┬¦58\n"
"- **Third term**: Uniform convergence gives you this everywhere\n"
"\n"
"The magic is that uniform convergence gives you control over the first and third terms **simultaneously** for all points.\n"
"\n"
"## A Historical Note\n"
"\n"
"This distinction between pointwise and uniform convergence was one of the great clarifications of 19th-century analysis. It helped mathematicians understand exactly when their intuitions about limits and continuity could be trusted.\n"
"\n"
"## Your Challenge\n"
"\n"
"Prove that the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous:\n"
"\n"
"**Lean signature**: ┬¦59\n"
"\n"
"Ready to fix Cauchy's \"mistake\" and see how the right kind of convergence preserves continuity? The ┬¦60 method awaits!"
msgstr ""

