msgid "# Level 1: Introduction to Function Limits\n"
"\n"
"Welcome to Lecture 20! We now shift our focus from sequences to **functions**. Just as we studied limits of sequences, we can study limits of functions as the input approaches a particular point.\n"
"\n"
"## The Definition\n"
"\n"
"**Definition (┬¦0):** We say that ┬¦1 has limit ┬¦2 at ┬¦3 if:\n"
"┬¦4\n"
"\n"
"This is written ┬¦5. (First the function, then the limit, then \"at\" ┬¦6.)\n"
"\n"
"**Reading the definition:** For *every* tolerance ┬¦7 around the output value ┬¦8, there exists a distance ┬¦9 around the input value ┬¦10 such that whenever ┬¦11 is within ┬¦12 of ┬¦13 (but not equal to ┬¦14), the function value ┬¦15 is within ┬¦16 of ┬¦17.\n"
"\n"
"## The Intuition\n"
"\n"
"The key difference from sequence limits is the condition ┬¦18. We care about what happens *near* c, but not at all about what happens *at* c. The function might not even be defined at ┬¦19!\n"
"\n"
"This is exactly what happens with the classic example:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦20\n"
"\n"
"At ┬¦21, the function is \"undefined\" (because it's ┬¦22; in Lean, this is equal to ┬¦23). But for ┬¦24, we can factor:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦25\n"
"\n"
"So as x approaches 1, ┬¦26 approaches some constant ┬¦27. Your job: figure out ┬¦28, and prove that it's the limit!\n"
"\n"
"## Your Challenge\n"
"\n"
"Prove that there exists a limit ┬¦29 such that:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦30\n"
"\n"
"In other words, prove that the function ┬¦31 has *some* limit as ┬¦32 approaches ┬¦33."
