#: Game.Levels.L22Lecture
msgid "# Lecture 22: Uniformity\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** I just noticed something about that last level.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Ugh. Ok, what was it?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** I don't know, you tell me.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** We proved that ┬¦0 was continuous everywhere. So what?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Right. How did we do it? What ┬¦1 did we choose, once ┬¦2 was given?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Are you getting senile, old man? We chose ┬¦3.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Anything interesting about that?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** What, that it has an ┬¦4 in it? So what? We had no other choice but to choose ┬¦5 depending on ┬¦6. We took ┬¦7 near ┬¦8, ┬¦9, and computed that ┬¦10 was ┬¦11.\n"
"The first factor is good, since it's less than ┬¦12; in the second factor,\n"
"since ┬¦13 is near ┬¦14, then ┬¦15 has size about ┬¦16, and we\n"
"added one just to be safe.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Ok, let's put a pin in this and come back to it later. Here's a question: suppose I have a sequence of continuous functions ┬¦17, and suppose ┬¦18 converges to some limit function ┬¦19.\n"
"That is, for every ┬¦20, the sequence of real numbers ┬¦21 converges to ┬¦22. What can you tell me about ┬¦23?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Is ┬¦24 continuous? Wait, I've fallen into this trap before. I even remember my counterexample from Lecture 1: Just take ┬¦25 on ┬¦26. Each ┬¦27 is continuous, but the limiting function is discontinuous at ┬¦28.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Exactly! So mere pointwise convergence isn't enough. But let's pretend that it was and see what goes wrong with our proof of continuity.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Ok, so you want me to try (and fail) to prove that ┬¦29 is continuous at some point ┬¦30. Given ┬¦31, we need to find ┬¦32 such that for all ┬¦33 with ┬¦34, we have ┬¦35.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Right. Go on.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Since ┬¦36 converges to ┬¦37 pointwise, for our given ┬¦38 and ┬¦39, we can find some big enough ┬¦40 such that for all ┬¦41, we have ┬¦42.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Yes. And?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Now, since ┬¦43 is continuous at ┬¦44, we can find some ┬¦45 such that for all ┬¦46 with ┬¦47, we have ┬¦48.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Good so far. Now, what would you like to do next?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Well, I want to show that ┬¦49 for ┬¦50 close to ┬¦51. I can use the triangle inequality:\n"
"┬¦52.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Excellent! And what can you say about each of these three terms?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Well, the middle term is less than ┬¦53 by our choice of ┬¦54. The last term is less than ┬¦55 by our choice of ┬¦56. So if I can make the first term less than ┬¦57, I'm done!\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** And can you?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Hmm... I need ┬¦58. Since ┬¦59 converges to ┬¦60 at the point ┬¦61, I can find some ┬¦62 (which might depend on ┬¦63) such that for ┬¦64, we have ┬¦65. Uh oh...\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** What's the problem?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** The problem is that my ┬¦66 was chosen to work at the specific point ┬¦67, but now I need it to work at this other point ┬¦68 too! And ┬¦69 could be **any** point near ┬¦70, so I'd need ┬¦71 to work at *all* of these points near ┬¦72 simultaneously.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Yeah, so what? No matter which ┬¦73 you pick, you can always find some ┬¦74 that works for that ┬¦75.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** But that's exactly the problem! The ┬¦76 I find depends on which ┬¦77 I'm looking at. For one ┬¦78, I might need ┬¦79. For another ┬¦80 nearby, I might need ┬¦81. And for yet another ┬¦82, I might need ┬¦83.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** So?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** So my original ┬¦84 was fixed at the beginning - it only depends on ┬¦85 and ┬¦86. But now I need this same fixed ┬¦87 to work for all possible values of ┬¦88 near ┬¦89. There's no guarantee that my fixed ┬¦90 is bigger than all the different ┬¦91's I'd need for different ┬¦92's!\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Ah, I see. So you're saying that even though ┬¦93 for each individual ┬¦94, there might not be a single ┬¦95 that makes the convergence happen \"fast enough\" simultaneously for all ┬¦96 in a neighborhood?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Exactly! The convergence might be happening at wildly different rates at different points. At some points it might converge quickly, at others very slowly.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Interesting. So what kind of convergence would you need to make this proof work?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** I'd need the convergence to be... uniform over the whole space? Or at least uniform over neighborhoods? So that I can find a single ┬¦97 that works for all points at once, not just point by point.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Precisely! You've just discovered why we need the concept of **uniform convergence**. Shall we make this precise?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Yes! What exactly do we mean by \"uniform convergence\"?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** You tell me.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Well, I said that I need a single ┬¦98 that works for all points at once. So instead of saying \"for each ┬¦99, there exists ┬¦100 such that for ┬¦101, we have ┬¦102\", I need to say \"there exists ┬¦103 such that for all ┬¦104 and all ┬¦105, we have ┬¦106\".\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Exactly! So uniform convergence means: for every ┬¦107, there exists ┬¦108 such that for all ┬¦109 and for all ┬¦110 in our domain, we have ┬¦111.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Got it! The key difference is the *order of quantifiers*. In pointwise convergence, we have \"for all ┬¦112, there exists ┬¦113\" - the ┬¦114 can depend on ┬¦115. In uniform convergence, we have \"there exists ┬¦116 such that for all ┬¦117\" - the same ┬¦118 must work for every point.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Perfect! This is *exactly* what Cauchy got **wrong** in his first attempt at proving that limits of continuous functions were continuous; he was missing uniformity! Ready to work on the proof?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Yes, let's do it!"
msgstr ""

