#: Game.Levels.L20Lecture
msgid "# Lecture 20: Function Limits\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** FUNCTIONS!!!\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Oh please don't shout, I'm standing right here.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Sorry! I just got a little over excited that we're moving on to functions.\n"
"Please tell me about them!\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Ah, right. Very good. Let's start at the beginning. What's the first thing you\n"
"learn in Calculus?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Hmmm. The derivative?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Ok, we can see about starting there. Tell me, what does it mean to\n"
"compute the derivative of a function ┬¦0 at some point ┬¦1.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Well, it's the slope of the tangent line.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Yes, of course; I mean, what expression are you trying to evaluate?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Oh! I remember: it's the limit as ┬¦2 of\n"
"┬¦3.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Which word there is problematic?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Ah, of course; \"limit\"! We don't know yet what limits are for functions. And I already know from experience that\n"
"you can't just stick in ┬¦4, since both the numerator and denominator vanish.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Right. So we need to figure out what it means for a limit of a *function* to exist. Let's think about this carefully. What do we want to be true when we write ┬¦5?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Well, we want ┬¦6 to get close to ┬¦7 when ┬¦8 gets close to ┬¦9.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Exactly! Now, do you remember our Engineer and Machinist from when we discussed sequence limits?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Yes! The Engineer specified a tolerance ┬¦10 for how close the output needed to be, and the Machinist replied with how many steps ┬¦11 were needed to guarantee that tolerance.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Perfect! Now with functions, there's a beautiful twist. The Engineer still specifies a tolerance ┬¦12 for the outputŌĆöthat is, we want ┬¦13. But what do you think the Machinist's response should be this time?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Hmm. With sequences, the Machinist said \"run the process for at least ┬¦14 steps.\" But with functions, we don't have \"steps\"... we have values of ┬¦15.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Precisely! So instead of saying \"wait ┬¦16 steps,\" how should the Machinist respond?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Oh! So the Machinist needs to give a tolerance on the *input* side, not a number of steps. So he needs to say something like: \"make sure your input ┬¦17 is within distance ┬¦18 of the target point ┬¦19\"?\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Exactly! The conversation goes like this:\n"
"\n"
"- **Engineer:** \"I need ┬¦20 to be within ┬¦21 of ┬¦22.\"\n"
"- **Machinist:** \"No problem! Just make sure your input ┬¦23 is within distance ┬¦24 of ┬¦25, and I'll guarantee your output tolerance.\"\n"
"\n"
"And just like with sequences, we say the limit exists if this conversation can continue for *any* tolerance ┬¦26 the Engineer demandsŌĆöthe Machinist can always respond with some appropriate ┬¦27.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** So the definition would be: for every ┬¦28, there exists a ┬¦29 such that if ┬¦30, then ┬¦31?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Beautifully stated! Yes, that's *almost* it. Let's write out what you said formally:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦32\n"
"\n"
"This is called an ┬¦33-┬¦34 definition. There's only one problem with this definition.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Hmm. I really don't see, what's wrong?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Well, think again back to informal calculus. What does it mean for a function\n"
"┬¦35\n"
" to be\n"
"*continuous* at ┬¦36.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Ok, that's when ┬¦37 exists, and is actually equal to the value of\n"
"┬¦38.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Yes, exactly! Remember when we spoke of derivatives, we don't want to evaluate\n"
"the limit when ┬¦39 is literally equal to zero, where we get ┬¦40. But look\n"
"again at your definition. Where do you ensure that?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Oh, I see! So we have to update the definition of a limit\n"
"to make sure that we don't actually allow ┬¦41. So does this work?\n"
"\n"
"┬¦42\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** That's the ticket! Some people write ┬¦43, but I think\n"
"it'll be easier to just record ┬¦44 separately.\n"
"The set of such ┬¦45 is called a *punctured neighborhood* of ┬¦46ŌĆöwe've removed the center point. This way, the limit only cares about the behavior of ┬¦47 *near* ┬¦48, not *at* ┬¦49.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** So this means ┬¦50 doesn't even need to be defined for the limit to exist?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Correct! Remember when you started learning calculus and had to do things like find the limit of ┬¦51 as ┬¦52 goes to ┬¦53?\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Yes! This function is undefined at ┬¦54 (actually in Lean, as I've learned, it's perfectly well defined, since ┬¦55 -- which means that it's certainly *not* continuous there...). But for ┬¦56, we can factor: ┬¦57. So ┬¦58, even though ┬¦59 doesn't exist!\n"
"\n"
"And this is exactly like the derivative situation. The difference quotient ┬¦60 is undefined at ┬¦61, but we can still take the limit as ┬¦62.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Precisely! You've understood the key point. The limit tells us about the *tendency* of a function as we approach a point, not necessarily what happens *at* that point.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** So to summarize:\n"
"- For limits, we assume ┬¦63 **and**  ┬¦64 (punctured neighborhood)\n"
"- For continuity, we only need ┬¦65; this is equivalent to:\n"
"the limit exists AND equals ┬¦66.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** You've got it! Let's go."
msgstr ""

