#: Game.Levels.L24Lecture
msgid "# Lecture 24: Topology\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** So wait, is \"compact\" just about being bounded?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Good question! Tell me about the function ┬¦0 on the interval ┬¦1. It's certainly continuous (as long as we don't include ┬¦2). The interval ┬¦3 is bounded. If that interval were compact, then ┬¦4 would be uniformly continuous on ┬¦5. Is ┬¦6 uniformly continuous on ┬¦7?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Ooh, doesn't look it; the slope gets really steep as ┬¦8 approaches ┬¦9. That means that if I want to keep the fluctuation of ┬¦10, that is, ┬¦11, small, I need to make ┬¦12 ever smaller and smaller, for ┬¦13 getting closer to ┬¦14. So I can't pick a single ┬¦15 that works for all ┬¦16 in ┬¦17.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Good. Can you see another way to see that ┬¦18 is not compact, directly from the definition?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Umm... I guess I could try to cover ┬¦19 with balls. Like, I could cover it with the balls ┬¦20. The ... Archimedean property (again!!) says that these balls cover all of ┬¦21. But if only finitely many of them are used, say up to ┬¦22, then the point ┬¦23 is not covered. So there's no finite subcover.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Excellent! So ┬¦24 is not compact; that is, being bounded is not enough for compactness. But it's easy to see that bounded *is* necessary. Can you see why?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Oh, I see it! Let ┬¦25 be our compact set. We can conver ┬¦26 by the balls ┬¦27 for all natural numbers ┬¦28. Since ┬¦29 is compact, there must be a finite subcover. That means that there is some largest ┬¦30 such that ┬¦31 covers all of ┬¦32. Therefore, ┬¦33 is bounded.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Perfect. So boundedness is necessary but, as we just saw with the example of ┬¦34, not sufficient for compactness. There's one more ingredient we need.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** What is it?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** The set also needs to be *closed*. Here's some more topology-speak for you: A set is *closed* if its complement is *open*.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Greaaaat, more definitions.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Last one, for now. A set ┬¦35 is *open* if: for every point in ┬¦36, there is a ball around that point which is entirely contained in ┬¦37. That is: ┬¦38 is open if:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦39\n"
"\n"
"Let's check your understanding: is a ball itself open?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Hmm let's see. I have a point ┬¦40. I have to find a ┬¦41 such that ┬¦42. The condition that ┬¦43 is in the ball means that ┬¦44, which looks something like this:\n"
"\n"
"---|(x-r)----(y)---(x)-------(x+r)|----\n"
"\n"
"So if we let ┬¦45, then ┬¦46 will fit inside ┬¦47. So yes, a ball is open!\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Excellent! So now you have all the ingredients to understand compactness in ┬¦48: A famous result called the *Heine-Borel Theorem* says that a set ┬¦49 is compact if and only if:\n"
"\n"
"it is closed and bounded.\n"
"\n"
"Heine proved this in 1872, and Borel generalized it to higher dimensions in 1895. This is a very important theorem in real analysis, because it allows us to easily check whether a set is compact or not. For example, the complement of ┬¦50 is the union of ┬¦51 and ┬¦52, both of which are open, so ┬¦53 is closed. And of course ┬¦54 is bounded. Therefore, by Heine-Borel, ┬¦55 is compact. This gives us the important result we wanted:\n"
"\n"
"**Theorem:** For any function that is continuous on a closed and bounded interval ┬¦56, the sequence of Riemann sums converges to a limit, which we call the integral of the function on ┬¦57.\n"
"\n"
"(Note again that ┬¦58 must be continuous on the *entire* closed interval ┬¦59. The function ┬¦60 is continuous on ┬¦61, all but one point; but the Riemann sums do not converge, because ┬¦62!)\n"
"\n"
"The proof is very simple: ┬¦63 is closed and bounded, and hence compact by Heine-Borel. Any function that is continuous on a compact set is uniformly continuous there. And if a function is uniformly continuous on an interval, then the Riemann sums converge to a limit. Just chain everything we've learned together!\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Wow, that's really elegant. How is Heine-Borel proved? I guess we already proved half of one direction, if a set is compact then it's bounded. How do we prove that it's also closed?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** You tell me!\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Ok, let's try. Suppose ┬¦64 is compact. We want to show that its complement ┬¦65 is open. So take any point ┬¦66. We need to show that there's a whole ball around ┬¦67 that stays away from ┬¦68. And the only way to make use of compactness is to cover ┬¦69 with balls. Oh, I think I see it!\n"
"\n"
"For every point ┬¦70, look at the ball centered at ┬¦71 of radius ┬¦72, say. That's a ball that contains ┬¦73 but stays away from ┬¦74. The collection of all such balls covers ┬¦75, and hence only finitely many such balls cover ┬¦76. So we have ┬¦77 and for each ┬¦78, we have a point ┬¦79 and a ball ┬¦80, and these finitely many balls cover ┬¦81. Now let ┬¦82 be the minimum of all the ┬¦83 for ┬¦84. Then the ball ┬¦85 stays away from all the balls covering ┬¦86, and hence from ┬¦87 itself. Therefore, ┬¦88 is open, and so ┬¦89 is closed.\n"
