"**SOCRATES:** Well done! You hardly need me anymore! :) Channel your inner me; what's the next thing I'd say?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** You'd tell me to try to prove the other direction. Ok, let's say that ┬¦90 is closed and bounded. We want to show that it's compact. So take any cover of ┬¦91 by balls. We need to find a finite subcover. I ... don't see what to do.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Ok, this direction is a bit harder. Let's build up to it with a few more definitions. (I know, I know.) Given a set ┬¦92 and a real number ┬¦93, we say that ┬¦94 is an *upper bound* for ┬¦95 if for all ┬¦96, ┬¦97. Easy, right? We say that ┬¦98 is a *least upper bound* (or *supremum*) for ┬¦99 if ┬¦100 is an upper bound for ┬¦101, and for any other upper bound ┬¦102, we have ┬¦103. In other words, ┬¦104 is the smallest of all upper bounds.\n"
"\n"
