"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Now, here's an important property of the real numbers: *every nonempty set of real numbers that is bounded above has a least upper bound*. This is called the *Least Upper Bound Property*. Let's talk about how you might go about proving it.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Hmm... Let me think. Ok, I start with at least one point ┬¦105, since ┬¦106 is nonempty, and at least one upper bound ┬¦107. I think I see what to do! Let's think about the middle point between ┬¦108 and ┬¦109, that is, ┬¦110. Is that an upper bound for ┬¦111? If not, then there exists some point ┬¦112 such that ┬¦113. Otherwise, if it *is* an upper bound, then we can set ┬¦114. In either case, we have a smaller interval ┬¦115 or ┬¦116. We can keep repeating this process, halving (or more) the interval each time. This gives us a sequence of nested intervals whose lengths go to zero. The bottoms are all points in ┬¦117 and increasing and bounded, hence have a limit ┬¦118. The tops are all upper bounds and decreasing and bounded, hence have a limit ┬¦119. Since the lengths of the intervals go to zero, ┬¦120. Now, I need to show that ┬¦121 is *the* least upper bound for ┬¦122. I think I can do that by showing that ┬¦123 is an upper bound, and that any smaller number is not an upper bound. Ok, I'm satisfied.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Excellent! Now, armed with the Least Upper Bound Property, you can finally prove that any closed and bounded set is compact. First let's prove that a closed interval ┬¦124 is compact. Take any cover of ┬¦125 by balls. We want to find a finite subcover. Consider the set ┬¦126 of all points ┬¦127 such that the interval ┬¦128 can be covered by finitely many of the balls. Clearly, ┬¦129, so ┬¦130 is nonempty. Also, every point in ┬¦131 is at most ┬¦132, so ┬¦133 is bounded above by ┬¦134. By the Least Upper Bound Property, ┬¦135 has a least upper bound ┬¦136. We want to show that ┬¦137. If not, then since the balls cover ┬¦138, there is some ball covering ┬¦139. Since the ball has positive radius, it covers some interval around ┬¦140, say ┬¦141. Since ┬¦142 is the least upper bound of ┬¦143, there must be some point ┬¦144 with ┬¦145. But then we can cover ┬¦146 with finitely many balls (since ┬¦147), and also cover ┬¦148 with the ball around ┬¦149. This gives us a finite cover for ┬¦150, contradicting the fact that ┬¦151 is an upper bound for ┬¦152. Therefore, ┬¦153, and hence ┬¦154 can be covered by finitely many balls.\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Ok, I'm with you. But what do we do for *any* closed and bounded set?\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Ah, and here's the last step. Any closed subset of a compact set is itself compact! Can you see why?\n"
"\n"
"**SIMPLICIO:** Hmm, let's see. Let ┬¦155 be a closed subset of a compact set ┬¦156. Take any cover of ┬¦157 by balls. We want to find a finite subcover. Since ┬¦158 is closed, its complement ┬¦159 is open. Therefore, for every point ┬¦160, there is a ball around ┬¦161 that stays within ┬¦162, that is, away from ┬¦163. The collection of all such balls, together with the balls covering ┬¦164, forms an open cover of the entire set ┬¦165. Since ┬¦166 is compact, there is a finite subcover of ┬¦167. This finite subcover must include finitely many balls covering ┬¦168, since the balls covering ┬¦169 do not cover any points in ┬¦170. Therefore, we have found a finite subcover for ┬¦171. Hence, ┬¦172 is compact. Nice! Since a bounded set is a subset of some closed interval ┬¦173, and we've just shown that ┬¦174 is compact, it follows that any closed and bounded set is compact.\n"
"\n"
"**SOCRATES:** Well done, Simplicio! You've just proved the Heine-Borel Theorem. And to bring it all the way back to calculus, this means that any continuous function on a closed and bounded interval ┬¦175 is uniformly continuous there, and hence Riemann integrable. Now let's do all this \"for real\"..."
