#: Game.Levels.L18Levels.L02
msgid "# Level 2: Alternating Series Test\n"
"\n"
"In this level, we prove one of the most elegant and useful results in the theory of infinite series: the **Alternating Series Test**, also known as the **Leibniz Test** (named after Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who discovered it in the 17th century).\n"
"\n"
"## The Setting\n"
"\n"
"Consider an alternating seriesŌĆöone where the signs alternate between positive and negative:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦0\n"
"\n"
"When does such a series converge?\n"
"\n"
"## The Theorem\n"
"\n"
"**Theorem** (┬¦1): Suppose ┬¦2 is an ┬¦3 sequence (meaning ┬¦4) that converges to ┬¦5. Then the alternating series\n"
"\n"
"┬¦6\n"
"\n"
"converges.\n"
"\n"
"In other words: *if the terms decrease to zero, then the alternating series converges*.\n"
"\n"
"**Note**: By ┬¦7 (to be proved in homework), since ┬¦8 and ┬¦9 is antitone, we automatically have ┬¦10 for all ┬¦11.\n"
"\n"
"## Classic Examples\n"
"\n"
"- The alternating harmonic series: ┬¦12 converges to ┬¦13\n"
"- The Leibniz formula for ┬¦14: ┬¦15\n"
"\n"
"## Proof Strategy\n"
"\n"
"The idea is to show that the **even** partial sums and **odd** partial sums both converge to the same limit:\n"
"- Even partial sums: ┬¦16 form a monotone increasing, bounded sequence\n"
"- Odd partial sums: ┬¦17 form a monotone decreasing, bounded sequence\n"
"- The difference ┬¦18, so they converge to the same limit\n"
"\n"
"This will require several technical lemmas (all to be proved in homework), but the main proof brings them all together beautifully!\n"
"\n"
"Your task: Prove the ┬¦19 by showing both even and odd subsequences of partial sums converge to the same limit.\n"
"\n"
"## New Theorems: look up: ┬¦20, ┬¦21, ┬¦22, ┬¦23, ┬¦24, ┬¦25, ┬¦26, and ┬¦27."
msgstr ""

