#: Game.Levels.L9Levels.L04_FiniteSums
msgid "# Level 1: Finite Sums\n"
"\n"
"Welcome to a new world of mathematics: **finite sums**! In this level, you'll prove that any individual term in a sum of absolute values is bounded by the total sum. This is a fundamental property that bridges discrete and continuous mathematics.\n"
"\n"
"## The Goal\n"
"\n"
"Prove that for any sequence ┬¦0 and natural number ┬¦1, every term ┬¦2 with ┬¦3 is at most the sum ┬¦4.\n"
"\n"
"Intuitively: if you're adding up a bunch of nonnegative numbers, no single number can be bigger than the total!\n"
"\n"
"## Strategy: Induction from the Start!\n"
"\n"
"­¤Ä» **Big Hint:** Even though the goal starts with ┬¦5, do **NOT** begin with ┬¦6. Instead, run **induction on ┬¦7** right from the beginning!\n"
"\n"
"This might feel counterintuitive, but trust the process. Induction gives you the perfect structure to peel off one term at a time using ┬¦8.\n"
"\n"
"### Your Induction Strategy:\n"
"- **Base case (┬¦9):** There are no natural numbers less than 0, so you'll get a ┬¦10\n"
"- **Inductive step (┬¦11):** Use ┬¦12 to write the sum for ┬¦13 as the sum for ┬¦14 plus the new term ┬¦15\n"
"  - Split into cases: Is ┬¦16 (use inductive hypothesis) or ┬¦17 (use nonnegativity)?\n"
"\n"
"## New Tools You'll Need\n"
"\n"
"### Summation Notation\n"
"┬¦18 means sum as ┬¦19 goes from ┬¦20 to ┬¦21 (which has ┬¦22 terms total!)\n"
"\n"
"### ┬¦23\n"
"Peels off the last term: ┬¦24\n"
"\n"
"### ┬¦25\n"
"If each term is nonnegative, so is the sum. Usage: ┬¦26, then prove ┬¦27\n"
"\n"
"### ┬¦28\n"
"If your hypotheses are contradictory (like ┬¦29 with ┬¦30), this tactic closes the goal immediately.\n"
"\n"
"### ┬¦31\n"
"Split into cases based on a decidable proposition. Usage: ┬¦32 creates two goals:\n"
"- One where ┬¦33 holds\n"
"- One where ┬¦34 holds\n"
"\n"
"Good luck! Remember: **induction first, then introduce ┬¦35!**"
msgstr ""

