#: Game.Levels.L24Levels.L02
msgid "# Compactness Ō¤╣ Closed and Bounded: Complete!\n"
"\n"
"Excellent! You've just proved that **compact Ō¤╣ closed**. Combined with Level 1, you've now established the full first direction of Heine-Borel:\n"
"\n"
"**Compact Ō¤╣ Closed and Bounded** Ō£ō\n"
"\n"
"**What Made This Proof Ingenious**:\n"
"- **The Separation Trick**: The key insight was using balls of radius ┬¦0 around points in ┬¦1. These balls contain points of ┬¦2 but can never reach the outside point ┬¦3.\n"
"- **Local to Uniform**: You converted the fact that ┬¦4 is separated from each individual point in ┬¦5 into uniform separation from the entire set ┬¦6. This is compactness at its finest!\n"
"- **Finite Extraction**: Once again, compactness let you reduce an infinite problem (separation from all points in ┬¦7) to a finite one (separation from finitely many covering balls).\n"
"\n"
"**The Geometric Picture**: Imagine trying to \"push\" the outside point ┬¦8 into the compact set ┬¦9. The proof shows this is impossible - there's always a \"safety buffer\" around ┬¦10 that keeps it separated from ┬¦11.\n"
"\n"
"**Why This Direction Is \"Easy\"**: Compactness gives you such strong control (every cover reduces to a finite subcover) that proving additional properties becomes manageable. The hard direction will be the converse!\n"
"\n"
"**What's Next**: Now comes the serious work. In Level 3, you'll prove the **Least Upper Bound Property** of ŌäØ - every bounded set has a supremum. This fundamental property of the real numbers is what makes the converse direction possible.\n"
"\n"
"**Looking Ahead**: Levels 4-5 will prove **Closed and Bounded Ō¤╣ Compact**. This is where the real analysis gets deep, and you'll see why the completeness of ŌäØ matters!\n"
"\n"
"The easy direction is done - now for the hard one! ­¤ÜĆ"
msgstr ""

