#: Game.Levels.L24Levels.L03
msgid "# Level 3: Least Upper Bound Property\n"
"\n"
"**The Big Picture**: We're taking a detour into the deep structure of ŌäØ itself. To prove that closed bounded sets are compact, we need a fundamental property (that does not hold for ŌäÜ!): **every bounded set has a supremum**.\n"
"\n"
"**New Definitions**:\n"
"- **Upper Bound**: ┬¦0\n"
"  - ┬¦1 sits above every point in ┬¦2\n"
"- **Least Upper Bound**: ┬¦3\n"
"  - ┬¦4 is an upper bound, and no smaller number is an upper bound\n"
"\n"
"**The Proof Strategy - Bisection**:\n"
"We'll construct a sequence of nested intervals ┬¦5 that shrink to the supremum. Here's where Lean's **dependent types** shine:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦6\n"
"\n"
"This type says: \"For each ┬¦7, give me a pair ┬¦8 such that:\n"
"- ┬¦9 (so the left endpoint is achievable)\n"
"- ┬¦10 is an upper bound for ┬¦11\n"
"- ┬¦12 (it's a valid interval)\n"
"- The interval length shrinks by half each time\"\n"
"\n"
"**The Inductive Construction**:\n"
"- **Base case**: Start with the ┬¦13 guaranteed by nonemptyness of ┬¦14, and given upper bound ┬¦15\n"
"- **Inductive step**: Given interval ┬¦16, look at midpoint ┬¦17\n"
"  - If ┬¦18 is an upper bound for ┬¦19, set ┬¦20\n"
"  - If not, find some ┬¦21 with ┬¦22, set ┬¦23\n"
"\n"
"**Dependent Types Magic**: The type system *guarantees* that our construction maintains all necessary properties at each step. We're not just building sequences - we're building sequences *with proofs* that they satisfy our constraints!\n"
"\n"
"**Your Mission**: Implement this bisection algorithm and prove that the limit sequences converge to the least upper bound of ┬¦24."
msgstr ""

