#: Game.Levels.L24Levels.L02
msgid "# Level 2: Heine-Borel Theorem: Part 1b\n"
"\n"
"**The Goal**: Complete the first direction of Heine-Borel by proving that every compact set is closed.\n"
"\n"
"**New Topology Vocabulary**:\n"
"- **Open Set**: ┬¦0\n"
"  - Translation: \"Around every point in ┬¦1, there's a whole ball that stays inside ┬¦2\"\n"
"  - Think: \"No boundary points belong to the set\"\n"
"- **Closed Set**: ┬¦3\n"
"  - Translation: \"The complement is open\"\n"
"  - Think: \"All boundary points belong to the set\"\n"
"\n"
"**The Challenge**: To prove ┬¦4 is closed, we need to prove ┬¦5 is open. That means: for any point ┬¦6, we need to find a ball around ┬¦7 that stays completely outside ┬¦8.\n"
"\n"
"**The Strategy - Separation by Compactness**:\n"
"1. **Local Separation**: For each point ┬¦9, the distance ┬¦10 is positive (since ┬¦11). Create a ball around ┬¦12 of radius ┬¦13 - this ball contains ┬¦14 but can't reach ┬¦15.\n"
"\n"
"2. **Covering**: These balls cover ┬¦16, so by compactness, finitely many suffice.\n"
"\n"
"3. **Uniform Separation**: Take the minimum of the finitely many separating distances. This gives you a uniform ┬¦17 such that ┬¦18 stays away from all of ┬¦19.\n"
"\n"
"**Why This Works**: You're using compactness to convert \"local separation\" (each point in ┬¦20 is some positive distance from ┬¦21) into \"uniform separation\" (there's a single ┬¦22 that works everywhere).\n"
"\n"
"**Your Mission**: Formalize this separation argument to show that ┬¦23 is open!"
msgstr ""

