#: Game.Levels.L19Levels.L02
msgid "# Congratulations!\n"
"\n"
"You've just proven the **Eventually Covers Property** for rearrangementsŌĆöa beautiful result about bijections of the natural numbers!\n"
"\n"
"## What We've Accomplished\n"
"\n"
"This theorem tells us that no matter how wildly a rearrangement ┬¦0 scrambles the natural numbers, it can't \"hide\" any element forever. Given any target set ┬¦1, there's a point ┬¦2 beyond which we're guaranteed to have seen all of these elements as outputs.\n"
"\n"
"## The Proof Technique\n"
"\n"
"The proof uses a clever construction:\n"
"1. Since ┬¦3 is surjective, each element ┬¦4 appears as ┬¦5 for some ┬¦6\n"
"2. We use the axiom of choice (via ┬¦7) to select all these preimages simultaneously\n"
"3. We set ┬¦8 larger than all the ┬¦9 values\n"
"4. Then for any ┬¦10, all the required preimages are in ┬¦11, so all their images are covered\n"
"\n"
"The key insight is that finite sets have maximum elements, so we can always find a threshold that works.\n"
"\n"
"## A Concrete Example\n"
"\n"
"Consider the rearrangement that sends:\n"
"- ┬¦12 (shift everything right)\n"
"- except ┬¦13 (one element goes way back)\n"
"\n"
"To cover ┬¦14 (just ┬¦15), we need ┬¦16, because ┬¦17 doesn't appear as ┬¦18 until ┬¦19.\n"
"\n"
"But the theorem guarantees such an ┬¦20 exists! No matter how we rearrange, we eventually catch everything.\n"
"\n"
"## Why This Matters for Series\n"
"\n"
"When we rearrange a series ┬¦21 to get ┬¦22, the partial sums are:\n"
"- Original: ┬¦23\n"
"- Rearranged: ┬¦24\n"
"\n"
"This theorem tells us that for large enough ┬¦25, the rearranged partial sum includes all the terms ┬¦26 from the original series. Combined with the strong Cauchy property from Level 1, this will let us prove that the rearranged series converges to the same limit!\n"
"\n"
"## Next Steps\n"
