#: Game.Levels.L25Levels.L02
msgid "# Level 2 **BIG BOSS**: Intermediate Value Theorem\n"
"\n"
"Welcome to the grand finale! We end our journey through formal real analysis with mathematics' most \"obvious\" theoremŌĆöone so intuitive that it was used without proof for over **2000 years**.\n"
"\n"
"**The Intermediate Value Theorem**: If a function ┬¦0 is continuous on a closed interval ┬¦1, with ┬¦2 and ┬¦3, then there exists some ┬¦4 such that ┬¦5.\n"
"\n"
"*Translation*: A continuous function that changes sign must cross zero somewhere.\n"
"\n"
"**Why is this the \"greatest\" theorem?** Because it captures something profound about the real numbers that we take for granted: there are **no gaps**. Unlike the rationals ŌäÜ (where ┬¦6 changes sign but never equals zero), the reals ŌäØ are **complete**.\n"
"\n"
"**Historical irony**: Ancient Greeks used this theorem in geometric constructions. Euler applied it freely. Even Bolzano and Cauchy assumed it initially. Yet the first rigorous proof wasn't given until 1817ŌĆöafter calculus had been developed for 150 years!\n"
"\n"
"**Why so hard to prove?** Because it requires the **Least Upper Bound Principle**ŌĆöthe very completeness of ŌäØ that distinguishes it from ŌäÜ. This \"obvious\" theorem actually encapsulates the deepest property of real numbers.\n"
"\n"
"Your proof will use *every major tool* we've built: suprema, continuity, proof by contradiction, and the intricate dance between topology and analysis. Ready for the ultimate challenge?"
msgstr ""

