#: Game.Levels.L19Levels.L02
msgid "# Level 2: Rearrangements\n"
"\n"
"In this level, we introduce the formal concept of a rearrangement and prove a crucial technical lemma about how rearrangements behave.\n"
"\n"
"## New Definitions\n"
"\n"
"**Definition** (┬¦0): A function ┬¦1 is *injective* (one-to-one) if whenever ┬¦2, we have ┬¦3. In other words, different inputs give different outputs.\n"
"\n"
"**Definition** (┬¦4): A function ┬¦5 is *surjective* (onto) if for every ┬¦6, there exists some ┬¦7 with ┬¦8. In other words, every output is achieved by some input.\n"
"\n"
"**Definition** (┬¦9): A function ┬¦10 is a *rearrangement* if it is both injective and surjectiveŌĆöthat is, a bijection of the natural numbers.\n"
"\n"
"A rearrangement ┬¦11 gives us a new ordering of ŌäĢ. For a sequence ┬¦12, the rearranged sequence ┬¦13 is defined by ┬¦14.\n"
"\n"
"## The Main Result\n"
"\n"
"**Theorem** (┬¦15): If ┬¦16 is a rearrangement, then for any ┬¦17, there exists ┬¦18 such that for all ┬¦19, we have:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦20\n"
"\n"
"In other words: the image of ┬¦21 on ┬¦22 contains ┬¦23.\n"
"\n"
"## What This Means\n"
"\n"
"Even though a rearrangement ┬¦24 might scramble the order of natural numbers dramatically, it must \"eventually catch up\" with the original ordering. By the time we reach index ┬¦25, we're guaranteed to have seen all of the first ┬¦26 elements as outputs of ┬¦27.\n"
"\n"
"For example, if ┬¦28 sends ┬¦29, we might have to wait a while, but eventually (before reaching some ┬¦30), all of ┬¦31 will have appeared as values ┬¦32 for ┬¦33.\n"
"\n"
"## Why This Matters\n"
"\n"
"This theorem is essential for proving that rearranged series converge to the same limit. We'll need to know that when we've computed enough terms of the rearranged series, we've included all the important early terms from the original series.\n"
"\n"
"Your task: Prove that every rearrangement eventually covers any initial segment!"
msgstr ""

