#: Game.Levels.L4Levels.L01_NonConverge
msgid "Step 3:\n"
"Once more, in natural language.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"## Natural Language Proof\n"
"\n"
"**Theorem:** The sequence ┬¦0, ┬¦1, ┬¦2, ┬¦3, ... does not converge.\n"
"\n"
"**Proof by contradiction:**\n"
"1. Suppose the sequence converges to some limit ┬¦4\n"
"2. Set ┬¦5 and apply the convergence definition\n"
"3. This guarantees some ┬¦6 such that ┬¦7 for all ┬¦8\n"
"4. Consider two specific indices: ┬¦9 and ┬¦10 (both are ┬¦11)\n"
"   - ┬¦12, so ┬¦13\n"
"   - ┬¦14, so ┬¦15.\n"
"5. But then:\n"
"\n"
"   ┬¦16\n"
"\n"
"     ┬¦17     [triangle inequality]\n"
"\n"
"     ┬¦18    [algebraic manipulation]\n"
"\n"
"     ┬¦19         [from steps above]\n"
"6. This gives us ┬¦20, which is impossible. QED\n"
"\n"
"## Key Insights\n"
"\n"
"- **Geometric intuition:** Any proposed limit L must be within 1/2 of both 1 and -1 simultaneously, but these values are distance 2 apart\n"
"- **Critical ╬Ą choice:** We chose ╬Ą = 1/2 strategically; larger values like ╬Ą = 1.5 wouldn't work since L = 0 could satisfy the constraints.\n"
"- **Triangle inequality:** The key step uses |a + b| Ōēż |a| + |b| to convert the distance between sequence values into a sum of distances from the limit.\n"
"\n"
"This proof exemplifies how rigorous definitions resolve historical mathematical debates and provide clear criteria for convergence."
msgstr ""

