#: Game.Levels.L13Levels.L03_MonotoneSubseq
msgid "# Level 1 **Big Boss:**  Monotone Subsequence\n"
"\n"
"Every sequence has hidden order within it. No matter how chaotic a sequence may appear, we can always extract a subsequence that moves consistently in one directionŌĆöeither always increasing (monotone) or always decreasing (antitone). This beautiful result, part of the classical Bolzano-Weierstrass theory, reveals that disorder is never complete.\n"
"\n"
"Our strategy hinges on a key observation: some positions in a sequence are **peaks**ŌĆöplaces from which the sequence never rises again. Either there are arbitrarily many such peaks (unbounded peaks), or there aren't. We'll prove that if peaks are *not* unbounded, then we can construct a monotone (non-decreasing) subsequence by cleverly avoiding the peaks entirely.\n"
"\n"
"## New Definitions\n"
"\n"
"**IsAPeak:** Standing at position ┬¦0, we say it's a peak if we can look down at all future values:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦1\n"
"\n"
"**UnBddPeaks:** A sequence has unbounded peaks if for any bound ┬¦2, there's always another peak beyond it:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦3\n"
"\n"
"**Conditional definition:** We can define functions by cases using ┬¦4. The proof ┬¦5 of the condition (or its negation) becomes available in each branch.\n"
"\n"
"## The Goal\n"
"\n"
"Prove that if a sequence ┬¦6 does **not** have unbounded peaks, then it has a **monotone** (non-decreasing) subsequence.\n"
"\n"
"The intuition: if peaks eventually stop appearing, the sequence must eventually start climbing. By taking an orbit starting beyond the last peak, each step moves to a position that's not a peakŌĆömeaning there's always somewhere higher to go next.\n"
"\n"
"(In the homework, you'll prove the complementary result: sequences *with* unbounded peaks have **antitone** subsequences. Just pick the peaks themselves!)\n"
"\n"
"## New Theorem\n"
"\n"
"**lt_of_not_ge:** If it's not true that ┬¦7, then ┬¦8.\n"
"\n"
"This simple fact lets us convert a failed inequality into a strict oneŌĆöessential for working with our conditional definition of the auxiliary sequence.\n"
"\n"
"## Strategy Outline\n"
"\n"
"1. **Extract witnesses:** Use ┬¦9 to get a bound ┬¦10 beyond which there are no peaks, and for each ┬¦11, get a witness ┬¦12 where ┬¦13\n"
"\n"
"2. **Build auxiliary sequence:** Define ┬¦14 that grows faster than identity everywhere\n"
"\n"
"3. **Take the orbit:** Let ┬¦15 be the n-fold iteration starting from ┬¦16\n"
"\n"
"4. **Verify monotonicity:** Since ┬¦17 always, we're always beyond the peaks, so ┬¦18\n"
"\n"
"Each piece builds on techniques from Lecture 12: ┬¦19 for extracting witnesses, orbits for building subsequences, and induction for verification. Now let's make it rigorous!"
msgstr ""

