#: Game.Levels.L6Levels.L02_LeftRight
msgid "# Level 3: Left and Right - Making Choices in Mathematics\n"
"\n"
"After mastering ┬¦0 to handle situations where we need to prove multiple things simultaneously, we now turn to a fundamentally different scenario: proving that at least one of several possibilities is true. This is the world of \"or\" statements (┬¦1), and it requires a completely different strategic approach.\n"
"\n"
"While ┬¦2 was about being comprehensiveŌĆöproving every part of a conjunctionŌĆöproving an \"or\" statement (\"disjunction\") is about making a strategic choice. When faced with proving \"P or Q,\" you don't need to prove both ┬¦3 and ┬¦4. You just need to prove one of them! This might seem easier, but it requires good mathematical judgment: which path should you choose?\n"
"\n"
"Think of this like a detective solving a case. To prove \"the butler did it OR the gardener did it,\" you don't need to prove both are guilty -- you just need solid evidence against *one* of them. The ┬¦5 and ┬¦6 tactics are your way of saying \"I'm going to focus my investigation on this suspect.\"\n"
"\n"
"In mathematical analysis, this choice-making appears everywhere. For instance, when proving that a sequence is bounded, you might show either that it's bounded above by some constant, or bounded below by another constant, or both. Sometimes one direction is much easier to establish than the other.\n"
"\n"
"## New Tools You'll Need\n"
"\n"
"- ┬¦7 and ┬¦8 tactics\n"
"\n"
"When your goal is to prove an \"Or\" statement, ┬¦9, you can do that by proving either ┬¦10 or ┬¦11. If you want to prove ┬¦12, then say ┬¦13, and the Goal will turn into ┬¦14.\n"
" If you want to prove ┬¦15, then say ┬¦16, and the Goal will turn into ┬¦17."
msgstr ""

