#: Game.Levels.L17Levels.L04
msgid "# Level 4: The Basel Problem\n"
"\n"
"Near the turn of the 18th century, the Bernoulli brothers Johann and Jakob became obsessed with evaluating the series:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦0\n"
"\n"
"This became known as the **Basel Problem** (after Basel, Switzerland, where the Bernoullis lived). Despite their considerable mathematical prowess, they could not find its exact value.\n"
"\n"
"It would take several more decades, and their most brilliant studentŌĆöthe legendary Leonhard EulerŌĆöto solve it in 1734. Euler showed that:\n"
"┬¦1.\n"
"\n"
"(Our series starts at k=2, so it equals ┬¦2, but that's a minor detail.)\n"
"\n"
"## Our More Modest Goal\n"
"\n"
"In this level, we won't compute the exact valueŌĆöthat requires Euler's revolutionary techniques connecting series to trigonometric functions. Instead, we'll prove something more fundamental: **the series converges at all**.\n"
"\n"
"## The Strategy: Comparison\n"
"\n"
"The key insight is to **compare** the Basel series with the Leibniz series from Levels 1-2. Observe that:\n"
"┬¦3\n"
"\n"
"Why? Because ┬¦4 for all ┬¦5.\n"
"\n"
"By the Series Order Theorem (Level 3), this means:\n"
"┬¦6\n"
"\n"
"So the partial sums of the Basel series are **bounded above by 1**!\n"
"\n"
"## New Theorems:\n"
"\n"
"**New Theorem (┬¦7):** The completeness of ┬¦8 (which we proved).\n"
"If a sequence of **real** numbers is Cauchy, then it converges.\n"
"Recall that we had already proved that every Cauchy sequence in ┬¦9 converges (┬¦10)\n"
"to a real number. So why are we proving the same theorem again, just with real-valued sequences?\n"
"Couldn't we have stated and proved it once and for all for either type, ┬¦11?\n"
"\n"
"No! The theorems are true for *completely different* reasons. ┬¦12 is true\n"
"by the **construction** of the real numbers (as equivalence classes of Cauchy sequences of rationals).\n"
"Meanwhile, ┬¦13 is true because of the **completeness** of the real numbers --\n"
"in fact, any \"completion\" of a metric space as equivalence classes of Cauchy sequences will\n"
"always be complete. Two different reasons / proofs, two different theorem statements.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"**New Theorem (┬¦14):** If a sequence ┬¦15 is:\n"
"- **Monotone:** ┬¦16 for all ┬¦17\n"
"- **Bounded:** ┬¦18 for all ┬¦19 and some ┬¦20\n"
"\n"
"We already proved that monotone bounded sequences are Cauchy (┬¦21). So\n"
"┬¦22 is simply combining\n"
"this with ┬¦23.\n"
"\n"
"## Your Task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that the Basel series converges by:\n"
"\n"
"1. **First**, prove ┬¦24 by combining ┬¦25 with completeness\n"
"\n"
"2. **Then**, apply it to ┬¦26 where ┬¦27, showing:\n"
"   - The partial sums are **bounded** by 1 (using comparison with Leibniz series)\n"
"   - The partial sums are **monotone** (adding positive terms)\n"
"\n"
"**Hints:**\n"
"- Use ┬¦28 to get the formula for the Leibniz partial sums\n"
"- Use ┬¦29 to compare Basel with Leibniz\n"
"- Use ┬¦30 to prove monotonicity\n"
"- The inequality ┬¦31 can be handled with ┬¦32 and ┬¦33\n"
"\n"
"This is a substantial proofŌĆöyou're standing on the shoulders of giants!"
msgstr ""

