#: Game.Levels.L5Levels.L01_DoubleSeqConv
msgid "# Level 1: Doubling Convergence\n"
"\n"
"After conquering the constant sequence, let's up our game: if a sequence converges, then doubling that sequence also converges, and converges to double the original limit.\n"
"\n"
"## The Factory Scaling Challenge\n"
"\n"
"Imagine our Machinist receives a challenge from the Engineer: 'Please double all the lengths, but maintain the same quality standards.' How should the Machinist respond?\n"
"\n"
"If the Engineer demands the doubled lengths be within ┬¦0 of ┬¦1, the Machinist can't just demand that the original process meet the original tolerance ┬¦2, because\n"
"\n"
"┬¦3,\n"
"\n"
"not ┬¦4. Instead, we must be more clever. Can you think of what to do?\n"
"\n"
"That's right, the ┬¦5 in the original process\n"
"is *arbitrary*, so we can play with it!\n"
"If we could get the original process can guarantee output within ┬¦6 of ┬¦7, then doubling that output will be within ┬¦8 of ┬¦9.\n"
"\n"
"This is the key insight: **when scaling by a constant, we need to scale our tolerance demands inversely**.\n"
"\n"
"## The Mathematical Setup\n"
"\n"
"Suppose we have:\n"
"- A sequence ┬¦10 that converges to ┬¦11\n"
"- A sequence ┬¦12 with the property that ┬¦13 for all ┬¦14\n"
"\n"
"We want to prove that ┬¦15 converges to ┬¦16.\n"
"\n"
"## Key Insight: Inverse Tolerance Scaling\n"
"\n"
"The crucial observation is that:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦17\n"
"\n"
"So if we want ┬¦18, we need ┬¦19, which means ┬¦20.\n"
"\n"
"This is exactly what we can get from the convergence of ┬¦21!\n"
"\n"
"## New Tools You'll Need\n"
"\n"
"**Absolute Value of Products**:\n"
"You'll need the new theorem ┬¦22 which states that for any real numbers ┬¦23 and ┬¦24:\n"
"\n"
"┬¦25.\n"
"\n"
"To use this theorem, you may find it convenient to\n"
"make a new hypothesis using ┬¦26 and then ┬¦27 by that hypothesis. That is, you can say,\n"
"\n"
"┬¦28\n"
"\n"
"and then ┬¦29 will replace ┬¦30 by ┬¦31 (either at the Goal, or ┬¦32 a hypothesis, if you so specify).\n"
"\n"
"## Your Strategic Approach\n"
"\n"
"1. Unfold the definition of convergence for the goal\n"
"2. Given any ┬¦33, use the convergence of ┬¦34 with tolerance ┬¦35. You may find it useful to separately prove the inequality ┬¦36 -- which\n"
"tactic do you think will help with that?\n"
"3. Extract the witness ┬¦37 from the convergence of ┬¦38\n"
"4. Use the same ┬¦39 for your sequence ┬¦40\n"
"5. Apply the scaling hypothesis and use ┬¦41 to relate ┬¦42 to ┬¦43\n"
"6. Use the convergence bound for ┬¦44 to conclude\n"
"\n"
"## Why This Pattern Matters\n"
"\n"
"This proof introduces the important technique of **inverse scaling** for tolerances. When you scale a sequence by a constant ┬¦45, you need to scale your tolerance demands by ┬¦46. This principle will appear again when you study:\n"
"- Products of sequences (where both factors contribute to the error)\n"
"- Derivatives (where the limit definition involves scaling by ┬¦47)\n"
"- Integration (where Riemann sums involve scaling by partition widths)\n"
"\n"
"The ability to manage how constants affect convergence is fundamental to all of analysis!"
msgstr ""

