#: Game.Levels.L24PsetIntro
msgid "# Problem Set 24\n"
"\n"
"Prove Problems 1 - 6 formally (in natural language); the rest can be proved using sketches of the main ideas.\n"
"\n"
"┬¦0 Prove that an arbitrary union of open sets is open.\n"
"\n"
"┬¦1 Prove that a finite intersection of open sets is open. Give a counterexample to show that an infinite intersection of open sets need not be open.\n"
"\n"
"┬¦2 Prove that an arbitrary intersection of closed sets is closed.\n"
"\n"
"┬¦3 Prove that a finite union of closed sets is closed. Give a counterexample to show that an infinite union of closed sets need not be closed.\n"
"\n"
"┬¦4 Prove that if a set ┬¦5 is closed, then it contains all its limit points; that is, if a sequence ┬¦6 in ┬¦7 converges to ┬¦8, then ┬¦9. (This is in fact what closed sets are \"closed\" under -- taking limits!)\n"
"\n"
"┬¦10 Prove that if a set ┬¦11 contains all its limit points (┬¦12), then it is closed.\n"
"\n"
"┬¦13 Give a different proof that a closed interval ┬¦14 is Closed. Suppose ┬¦15 is a sequence in ┬¦16 converging to ┬¦17. Show that ┬¦18. [Hint: Try the Order Limit Theorem from Lecture 10, Level 2...]\n"
"\n"
"┬¦19 Let ┬¦20 be a set of reals, and let ┬¦21 be the set of its limit points (that is, the set of all ┬¦22 such that there exists a sequence ┬¦23 in ┬¦24 converging to ┬¦25). Show that if ┬¦26 is a limit point of ┬¦27, then ┬¦28 is a limit point of ┬¦29. That is, no new limit points are created when we pass from ┬¦30 to its \"closure\" ┬¦31. [Hint: Remember how we proved that the real numbers are complete?...]\n"
"\n"
"┬¦32 Prove that if ┬¦33 is compact, then any sequence ┬¦34 in ┬¦35 has a subsequence that converges to a limit in ┬¦36. The latter property is called *sequential compactness*.\n"
"\n"
"┬¦37 Conversely, prove that if ┬¦38 is sequentially compact (that is, every sequence in ┬¦39 has a subsequence converging to a limit in ┬¦40), then it is compact.\n"
"\n"
"┬¦41Ōŗå (Optional!) Let ┬¦42 denote the \"Cantor set\". This is constructed as follows. Start with the closed interval ┬¦43. Remove the open middle third ┬¦44, leaving the two closed intervals ┬¦45 and ┬¦46. Now remove the open middle thirds of these two intervals, leaving four closed intervals: ┬¦47, ┬¦48, ┬¦49, and ┬¦50. Continue this process indefinitely. The Cantor set ┬¦51 is defined as the intersection of all these sets obtained at each step. Show that the Cantor set ┬¦52 is closed and hence compact. A point ┬¦53 in a set ┬¦54 is said to be an *isolated point* of ┬¦55 if there exists a ball ┬¦56 that contains no other points of ┬¦57 except for ┬¦58 itself; that is, there is no nontrivial sequence in ┬¦59 converging to ┬¦60. A set ┬¦61 is called *perfect* if it has no isolated points, that is, its every point is a nontrivial limit point.\n"
"Show that the Cantor set is perfect."
msgstr ""

