#: Game.Levels.L17Levels.L03
msgid "Perfect! You've proven a fundamental monotonicity property of series.\n"
"\n"
"## What You've Proven\n"
"\n"
"**Theorem (SeriesOrderThm):** If ┬¦0 for all ┬¦1, then:\n"
"┬¦2 for all ┬¦3\n"
"\n"
"That is, term-by-term inequalities are preserved in partial sums.\n"
"\n"
"## The Proof Technique\n"
"\n"
"Your induction proof was beautifully straightforward:\n"
"- **Base case:** Empty sums are equal, so ┬¦4\n"
"- **Inductive step:** Split each sum using ┬¦5, apply the inductive hypothesis to the first ┬¦6 terms, and use ┬¦7 for the last term\n"
"\n"
"The inequality ┬¦8 followed immediately from combining two simpler inequalities!\n"
"\n"
"## Why This Is Powerful\n"
"\n"
"This theorem is the cornerstone of **comparison tests** for series convergence. Here's the typical application:\n"
"\n"
"**Comparison Test Setup:**\n"
"- Suppose ┬¦9 for all ┬¦10\n"
"- Suppose the series ┬¦11 converges to some limit ┬¦12\n"
"\n"
"**Conclusion:** The series ┬¦13 also converges, and ┬¦14.\n"
"\n"
"**Why?** By your theorem, every partial sum satisfies ┬¦15. So the sequence ┬¦16 is monotone increasing (adding positive terms) and bounded above by ┬¦17. Therefore it must converge!\n"
"\n"
"## Taking Limits\n"
"\n"
"An important consequence: if ┬¦18 for all ┬¦19, and both infinite series converge, then:\n"
"┬¦20\n"
"\n"
"This follows by taking limits on both sides of your partial sum inequality. Limits preserve weak inequalities!\n"
"\n"
"## Preview: The Basel Problem\n"
"\n"
"In the next level, we'll use this theorem to prove that the famous **Basel series** converges:\n"
"┬¦21\n"
"\n"
"The strategy: compare it with the Leibniz series! Since ┬¦22, your theorem tells us the Basel series has smaller partial sums. Since the Leibniz series converges to 1, the Basel series is bounded above by 1.\n"
"\n"
"Combined with the fact that the Basel series is monotone increasing (adding positive terms), this will prove convergence!\n"
"\n"
"## General Principle\n"
"\n"
"Your theorem exemplifies a key principle in analysis: **order structure is preserved under limits**. This makes inequality reasoning a powerful tool throughout real analysis.\n"
"\n"
"---\n"
"\n"
"**Next:** Time to tackle the Basel ProblemŌĆöone of the most famous series in mathematical history!"
